# Dev Lite Commit Rules

This workflow uses small, focused commits.

## Branch Safety

Do not push directly to `main`, `master`, or the repository default branch
during this workflow unless the user explicitly asks for that exact behavior.

Before implementation, check the current branch. If work is on the default
branch, create or ask to create a focused feature/fix branch such as
`dev/<short-feature-name>` or `fix/<short-bug-name>`.

Keep commits on the feature/fix branch. After final PR readiness review passes,
push the branch if needed and open a PR or provide the exact PR command and
description for the user to run.

Do not merge the PR, squash, rebase public history, or push to the default
branch unless the user explicitly asks.

## Commit Timing

Commit after each completed task.

Commit again after phase review fixes, if any.

Do not combine unrelated tasks into one commit.

## Commit Scope

Each commit should map to one of these:

- One completed task
- One test-only improvement
- One bug fix found during phase review
- One review-fix batch after a phase review
- One cleanup/refactor explicitly called out in the plan

## Preferred Commit Format

Use concise conventional-style messages when possible:

```text
feat: add [task summary]
fix: address [issue summary]
test: add coverage for [behavior]
refactor: simplify [area]
docs: update [doc or README area]
chore: update [tooling/config]
```

## Commit Summary Should Include

When suggesting a commit, include:

- What changed
- Why it changed
- Tests/checks run
- Any known risks

## Avoid Committing

Do not commit:

- Temporary debugging
- Generated noise
- Unrelated formatting
- Half-finished task work
- Future-phase work mixed into current task work
